-- PRESS DIGEST -Hong Kong - March 28
-- By Donny Kwok
-- Thu Mar 27, 2014 10:04PM EDT
-- None



HONG KONG, March 28 (Reuters) - These are some of the leading stories in Hong Kong newspapers on Friday. Reuters has not verified these stories and does not vouch for their accuracy.

SOUTH CHINA MORNING POST  -- China is expected to introduce its own version of the new US tax law that requires financial institutions around the world to provide Washington with information on US taxpayers, analysts say. Such a law would make it more difficult for corrupt Chinese officials and their relatives to park their wealth in Hong Kong. (http://link.reuters.com/tyh97v) -- MTR <0066.HK> passengers will face fare increases of 3.6 per cent in June - the fifth year in a row that the railway company has raised its fares despite making a HK$13 billion ($1.68 billion) net profit last year. (http://link.reuters.com/zyh97v) -- While the consumption of luxury goods in mainland China fell sharply last year, online interest in upmarket Swiss watches there remained the highest worldwide, a study from WorldWatchReport's latest edition has found. (http://link.reuters.com/caj97v)  THE STANDARD -- Senior mainland officials have agreed to allocate half a day to discuss political reform with legislators during their visit to Shanghai next month, Hong Kong Chief Executive Leung Chun-ying says. (http://link.reuters.com/faj97v) -- Employers say that workers using smartphone application WhatsApp to apply for sick leave are irresponsible, a survey has found. Local employers interviewed by Tamty McGill Consultants International said that using phone apps rather than a direct call or e-mail is unacceptable. (http://link.reuters.com/haj97v) -- Wharf Holdings <0004.HK> is conservative on its retail sales growth this year amid slower demand for luxury goods from mainlanders. Deputy chairman Stephen Ng said sales of high-priced products at malls have slowed while those for cheaper daily necessity goods are good. (http://link.reuters.com/paj97v)  HONG KONG ECONOMIC JOURNAL  -- Children's online game developer BAIOO Family Interactive opens the retail book on Friday, selling shares at  prices between HK$2 and HK$2.6 apiece in a Hong Kong initial public offering, raising up to HK$1.84 billion ($237.17 million).  HONG KONG ECONOMIC TIMES  -- Demand for land in Beijing is seen cooling down with latest sale of five pieces of land fetching an aggregate 8 billion yuan ($1.29 billion), below market forecast of 9 billion yuan.